Generics:
Generics allows you to write classes, interfaces and methods with
a placeholder for types.

<String, Integer>
<T>

Why Generics?
i)Type Safety
ii)Reusable code
iii)No need for casting
iv)Cleaner code
v)Backward Compatibility


Generic Class:
A class with type parameter.

class Box<T>
{
 private T value;
 
 public void set(T value)
 {
  this.value=value; 
 }
 
  public T get()
 {
   return value; 
 }
 
} 

Generic Method:
Methods that define their own type parameters.
 
 Bounded Generics: Restrict the type parameter.own
 
 Wildcard : ? - Used when you dont know the exact type
 
 List<?> list=new ArrayList<?>(); //Unbounded wildcard
 //can hold any type
 
 List <? extends Number> list;//Upperbounded wildcard
 //can read values as numbers
 
 List <? super Integer> list;//Lowerbounder wildcard
 //can add Interger or subclass
 
 